 have appeared to date. In this Ethnology supplement, anthropologists who have carried out long-term fieldwork among indigenous people review the ethnographic literature in the various regions of Middle America and discuss the theoretical and methodological orientations that have framed the work of areal scholars over the last several decades. They examine how research agendas have developed in relationship to broader interests in the field and the ways in which the anthropology of the region has responded to the sociopolitical and economic policies of Mexico and Guatemala. Most importantly, they focus on the changing conditions of life of the indigenous peoples of Mesoamerica. This volume thus offers a comprehensive picture of both the indigenous populations and developments in the anthropology of the region over the last thirty years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndians of Central America. 0aIndians of Mexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBricker, Victoria Reifler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBricker, Victoria Reifler, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jeffrey H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDow, James W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Catharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKöhler, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonaghan, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonaghan, John D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMulhare, Eileen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSandstrom, 